## Common Pitfalls

### Analysis Paralysis

Wrong: Spend 6 months on market research before making any strategic decisions. Require certainty before acting.

Right: Time-box research to 2-4 weeks. Make decisions with 70% confidence. Use real market feedback to fill the remaining 30%.

### Confirmation Bias in Research

Wrong: Design survey questions that lead respondents toward your desired answer. Only interview customers who love your product.

Right: Ask open-ended questions. Interview churned customers and lost deals. Actively seek disconfirming data.

### Static Market View

Wrong: Treat a market analysis from 18 months ago as current. Assume segments and competitors have not changed.

Right: Refresh competitive intelligence quarterly. Re-validate segment assumptions annually. Markets move faster than PowerPoint decks.

### Ignoring Adjacent Markets

Wrong: Only monitor direct competitors. Miss the startup three categories away that is about to redefine your market.

Right: Monitor adjacent markets, emerging technologies, and cross-industry trends. Disruption usually comes from outside your current competitive set.
